    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-02T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-02T13:00:00-05:00" n="342"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d342">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.6211/170: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-02T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 2, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 2—4:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1743. The Polish Ambassador<note n="26" xml:id="d342fn26">Juljusz
                        Lukasiewicz.</note> informed me today that the Soviet Ambassador in
                        Warsaw<note n="27" xml:id="d342fn27">Nikolay I. Sharonov.</note> had called
                    on Beck yesterday and had stated that the Soviet Government considered it
                    extraordinary that the Polish Government had not noted the passage in
                    Voroshilov’s speech<note n="28" xml:id="d342fn28">For a report of Marshal
                        Voroshilov’s interview with a correspondent of <hi rend="italic"
                            >Izvestiya</hi>, published on August 27, 1939, see telegram No. 476,
                        August 27, 3 p.m., from the Ambassador in the Soviet Union, <ref
                            target="#pg_311">p. 311</ref>. See also the Polish White Book, doc. Nos.
                        170, 171, 172, and 173, pp. 187–189.</note> in which he had stated that the
                    agreement between Germany and the Soviet Union would not interfere with
                    commercial exchanges between Poland and the Soviet Union. The Soviet Union was
                    prepared to continue to provide commercial supplies to Poland.</p>
                <p>It is difficult to interpret this statement of the Soviet Ambassador to Beck in
                    view of the arrival of a Soviet military mission in Berlin. It may mean that the
                    Soviet Government intends to give doses of support to both sides in the war
                    which has now begun with a view to <pb facs="0361" n="349" xml:id="pg_349"/>
                    keeping the war going as long as possible so that suffering may be prolonged to
                    the extreme and that in the end the Soviet armies intact will be able to march
                    over the Continent.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
